  {
    "eu_id": "EU-0004",
    "kind": "visual_panel",
    "page": "newspaper_The Wall Street Journal - 2025-01-08@magazinesclubnew_page_021",
    "primary_id": "mineru_newspaper_The Wall Street Journal - 2025-01-08@magazinesclubnew_page_021_46",
    "source": "visual_seed",
    "member_count": 43,
    "elements": [
      {
        "id": "mineru_newspaper_The Wall Street Journal - 2025-01-08@magazinesclubnew_page_021_7",
        "observed_type": "text",
        "canon_role": "support_paragraph",
        "text": "",
        "bbox": [
          0.17654557042702357,
          0.10312723800429696,
          0.32950924155513067,
          0.14195909922813718
        ],
        "order": 4
      },
      {
        "id": "mineru_newspaper_The Wall Street Journal - 2025-01-08@magazinesclubnew_page_021_2",
        "observed_type": "text",
        "canon_role": "support_paragraph",
        "text": "New Mountain Capital is selling its stake in accounting firm Citrin Cooperman to an investor group led by Black- stone, the fi rst flip of an audit firm by a private-equity inves- tor.",
        "bbox": [
          0.012746972594008922,
          0.11585899578260524,
          0.16443594646271512,
          0.16010185406222646
        ],
        "order": 5
      },
      {
        "id": "mineru_newspaper_The Wall Street Journal - 2025-01-08@magazinesclubnew_page_021_26",
        "observed_type": "text",
        "canon_role": "support_paragraph",
        "text": "ter the North- western Mutual commitment. The firm was founded in 2009by 10 partners, many of whom had previously worked to- gether under Chief Executive Alan Waxman at Goldman Sachs. The partners were ini- snapping up a portfolio of mortgages in the aftermath of the financial crisis, for exam- ple. Now it is investing more consistently as banks have scaled back in response to regulatory pressure.",
        "bbox": [
          0.7144678138942001,
          0.11936022917164,
          0.8215423836838751,
          0.30333412906819446
        ],
        "order": 6
      },
      {
        "id": "mineru_newspaper_The Wall Street Journal - 2025-01-08@magazinesclubnew_page_021_13",
        "observed_type": "text",
        "canon_role": "support_paragraph",
        "text": "Northwestern Mutual to take a small minority stake in investment firm",
        "bbox": [
          0.3409815168897387,
          0.12222487467175937,
          0.4888463989802422,
          0.15946526617331105
        ],
        "order": 7
      },
      {
        "id": "mineru_newspaper_The Wall Street Journal - 2025-01-08@magazinesclubnew_page_021_19",
        "observed_type": "text",
        "canon_role": "support_paragraph",
        "text": "pany it helped create in the aftermath of the 2008-2009 fi- nancial crisis. Other private- equity firms such as KKR, Blackstone and Brookfield have since bought insurers or struck deals to manage their assets.",
        "bbox": [
          0.5041427660930529,
          0.12254316861621707,
          0.6583811344805609,
          0.17315190578499243
        ],
        "order": 8
      },
      {
        "id": "mineru_newspaper_The Wall Street Journal - 2025-01-08@magazinesclubnew_page_021_27",
        "observed_type": "text",
        "canon_role": "support_paragraph",
        "text": "",
        "bbox": [
          0.8330146590184832,
          0.12286146256067479,
          0.9859783301465902,
          0.167104320840296
        ],
        "order": 9
      },
      {
        "id": "mineru_newspaper_The Wall Street Journal - 2025-01-08@magazinesclubnew_page_021_24",
        "observed_type": "text",
        "canon_role": "support_paragraph",
        "text": "",
        "bbox": [
          0.6666666666666666,
          0.12317975650513249,
          0.8209050350541747,
          0.20625447600859392
        ],
        "order": 10
      },
      {
        "id": "mineru_newspaper_The Wall Street Journal - 2025-01-08@magazinesclubnew_page_021_9",
        "observed_type": "text",
        "canon_role": "support_paragraph",
        "text": "Blackstone, which manages about $55 billion in assets, would be one of the largest private-equity firms to have a stake in an accounting firm. A group led by Hellman & Fried- man, which managed $120 bil- lion in assets at the end of 2023, bought a stake in Baker Tily in June. Blackstone par- ticipated in the debt on that deal, providing $450 million of a $1 billion financing package.",
        "bbox": [
          0.17590822179732313,
          0.1429139810615103,
          0.3301465901848311,
          0.22535211267605634
        ],
        "order": 11
      },
      {
        "id": "mineru_newspaper_The Wall Street Journal - 2025-01-08@magazinesclubnew_page_021_3",
        "observed_type": "text",
        "canon_role": "support_paragraph",
        "text": "The deal, which would value Citrin Cooperman at more than $2 billion, is the latest in a series of stakes that private-equity firms are taking in midsize audit and consult- ing firms in the U.S. Account- ing firms are hungry for more money to pay for technology and talent. Many private-eq- uity funds consider account- ing firms to be low-risk in- vestments that could net a sizable return based in part on recurring revenue streams.",
        "bbox": [
          0.012109623964308477,
          0.16073844195114187,
          0.16443594646271512,
          0.2562266252884539
        ],
        "order": 12
      },
      {
        "id": "mineru_newspaper_The Wall Street Journal - 2025-01-08@magazinesclubnew_page_021_28",
        "observed_type": "text",
        "canon_role": "support_paragraph",
        "text": "Dryden's group last month announced a deal to buy as much as $4 billion of loans from buy-now-pay-later plat- form Affirm.",
        "bbox": [
          0.8330146590184832,
          0.16742261478475373,
          0.9853409815168898,
          0.19893371528606668
        ],
        "order": 14
      },
      {
        "id": "mineru_newspaper_The Wall Street Journal - 2025-01-08@magazinesclubnew_page_021_22",
        "observed_type": "text",
        "canon_role": "support_paragraph",
        "text": "For many firms, private $13B Amount of Northwestern Mutual's assets involved in the deal best opportunities arise. \"If someone gave me $13 billion and said go invest it to- morrow, I might be able to do it, but I probably wouldn't be able to do it in the best risk- adjusted-return way,\" said Mi- chael Muscolino, a Sixth Street co-founder who leads its financial-services efforts. Based in San Francisco, Sixth Street will manage more than $100 billion in assets af- tially backed by TPG but sepa- rated from it in 2020. Sixth Street built a team of 40 people focused on asset- based finance, hiring Michael Dryden from Credit Suisse in 2022 to lead its expansion. The firm had historically in- vested in asset-based finance in a more opportunistic way,",
        "bbox": [
          0.5060548119821542,
          0.17410678761836557,
          0.65710643722116,
          0.20625447600859392
        ],
        "order": 15
      },
      {
        "id": "mineru_newspaper_The Wall Street Journal - 2025-01-08@magazinesclubnew_page_021_18",
        "observed_type": "list",
        "canon_role": "support_paragraph",
        "text": "credit has largely been synon- ymous with lending to midsize companies, often to finance their buyouts by a private-eq- uity firm. As managers in- creasingly take in cash from in- surance compa- nies, they are moving deeper into strategies aimed at pro- viding better returns than corporate bonds while re- maining rela-",
        "bbox": [
          0.5035054174633524,
          0.17506166945173868,
          0.5901848311026131,
          0.2944218986233787
        ],
        "order": 16
      },
      {
        "id": "mineru_newspaper_The Wall Street Journal - 2025-01-08@magazinesclubnew_page_021_15",
        "observed_type": "text",
        "canon_role": "support_paragraph",
        "text": "Investment firm sixth Street is forging a partnership with Northwestern Mutual to manage $13 billion of the in- surer's assets, executives from the companies said. The money will primarily be in- vested in asset-based finance, a hot area that encompasses a swath of consumer lending, including mortgages, credit- card loans and auto loans.",
        "bbox": [
          0.3397068196303378,
          0.17951778467414659,
          0.4933078393881453,
          0.2565449192329116
        ],
        "order": 17
      },
      {
        "id": "mineru_newspaper_The Wall Street Journal - 2025-01-08@magazinesclubnew_page_021_29",
        "observed_type": "text",
        "canon_role": "support_paragraph",
        "text": "Sixth Street has a separate team of 25 people solely fo- cused on insurance. It owns and advises on the invest- ments for Talcott Financial Group, an annuities company with $127 billion in assets.",
        "bbox": [
          0.8330146590184832,
          0.1995703031749821,
          0.9847036328871893,
          0.24317657356568792
        ],
        "order": 18
      },
      {
        "id": "mineru_newspaper_The Wall Street Journal - 2025-01-08@magazinesclubnew_page_021_23",
        "observed_type": "text",
        "canon_role": "support_paragraph",
        "text": "",
        "bbox": [
          0.5959209687699172,
          0.21071059123100183,
          0.727214786488209,
          0.27882549534495105
        ],
        "order": 19
      },
      {
        "id": "mineru_newspaper_The Wall Street Journal - 2025-01-08@magazinesclubnew_page_021_8",
        "observed_type": "text",
        "canon_role": "support_paragraph",
        "text": "The sale allows New Moun- tain to focus on boosting reve- nue at Grant Thornton's U.S. unit, in which it acquired a stake last May. New Mountain aims to merge Grant Thorn- ton's nonaudit services in the U.S. and more than 10 other international units over the next five years, primarily in Europe and Asia, a person fa- miliar with the plans said.",
        "bbox": [
          0.1752708731676227,
          0.22471552478714094,
          0.3301465901848311,
          0.30110607145699053
        ],
        "order": 20
      },
      {
        "id": "mineru_newspaper_The Wall Street Journal - 2025-01-08@magazinesclubnew_page_021_30",
        "observed_type": "text",
        "canon_role": "support_paragraph",
        "text": "Northwestern Mutual is owned by its policyholders. The company, which was founded more than 165 years ago, provides life, disability- income and long-term-care in- surance, annuities, and bro- kerage and wealth advisory. It manages the bulk of its $627 billion in assets internally and has invested in private mar- kets for decades.",
        "bbox": [
          0.8330146590184832,
          0.24349486751014562,
          0.9847036328871893,
          0.3195671202355375
        ],
        "order": 21
      },
      {
        "id": "mineru_newspaper_The Wall Street Journal - 2025-01-08@magazinesclubnew_page_021_4",
        "observed_type": "text",
        "canon_role": "support_paragraph",
        "text": "The Blackstone-led group would take a more than two- thirds ownership stake in Cit- rin, and Blackstone itself holds an interest in the range of 40% to 45% in the group, peo- ple familiar with the transac- tion said.",
        "bbox": [
          0.012746972594008922,
          0.25590833134399615,
          0.16379859783301465,
          0.30779024429060237
        ],
        "order": 22
      },
      {
        "id": "mineru_newspaper_The Wall Street Journal - 2025-01-08@magazinesclubnew_page_021_16",
        "observed_type": "text",
        "canon_role": "support_paragraph",
        "text": "Milwaukee-based North- western Mutual also will take a small minority stake in Sixth Street, bolstering the invest- ment firm's balance sheet to help it fund growth. The stake is of a similar size to the roughly 10% holding Sixth Street bought back from pri- vate-equity firm TPG last year, according to people familiar with the matter.",
        "bbox": [
          0.3397068196303378,
          0.2562266252884539,
          0.49394518801784576,
          0.3322988780138458
        ],
        "order": 23
      },
      {
        "id": "mineru_newspaper_The Wall Street Journal - 2025-01-08@magazinesclubnew_page_021_20",
        "observed_type": "text",
        "canon_role": "support_paragraph",
        "text": "tively low-risk. Insurers invest customers' premiums with the goal of earning more than they must pay out to policy- holders.",
        "bbox": [
          0.5047801147227533,
          0.294103604678921,
          0.6577437858508605,
          0.32625129306914935
        ],
        "order": 24
      },
      {
        "id": "mineru_newspaper_The Wall Street Journal - 2025-01-08@magazinesclubnew_page_021_25",
        "observed_type": "text",
        "canon_role": "support_paragraph",
        "text": "",
        "bbox": [
          0.6673040152963671,
          0.2950584865122941,
          0.8215423836838751,
          0.3654014482374473
        ],
        "order": 25
      },
      {
        "id": "mineru_newspaper_The Wall Street Journal - 2025-01-08@magazinesclubnew_page_021_11",
        "observed_type": "text",
        "canon_role": "support_paragraph",
        "text": "Regulators say they are concerned about potential conflicts of interest from the accounting profession's grow- ing ties to private equity, given that an auditor's objec- tivity is critical to the busi-",
        "bbox": [
          0.17654557042702357,
          0.30078777751253283,
          0.32950924155513067,
          0.34885016312564654
        ],
        "order": 26
      },
      {
        "id": "mineru_newspaper_The Wall Street Journal - 2025-01-08@magazinesclubnew_page_021_5",
        "observed_type": "text",
        "canon_role": "support_paragraph",
        "text": "Citrin Cooperman, a New York-based accounting firm, in October 2021 sold a majority stake to New Mountain, which has about $55 billion in assets under management.",
        "bbox": [
          0.012746972594008922,
          0.30747195034614466,
          0.16443594646271512,
          0.34503063579215404
        ],
        "order": 27
      },
      {
        "id": "mineru_newspaper_The Wall Street Journal - 2025-01-08@magazinesclubnew_page_021_31",
        "observed_type": "text",
        "canon_role": "support_paragraph",
        "text": "But Northwestern Mutual didn't have the capability of finding and structuring asset- based finance deals, a labor- intensive process, according to Jeb Bentley, its chief invest- ment officer.",
        "bbox": [
          0.8330146590184832,
          0.3202037081244529,
          0.9847036328871893,
          0.36412827245961643
        ],
        "order": 28
      },
      {
        "id": "mineru_newspaper_The Wall Street Journal - 2025-01-08@magazinesclubnew_page_021_21",
        "observed_type": "text",
        "canon_role": "support_paragraph",
        "text": "Unlike most of the deals done by its publicly traded ri- vals, Sixth Street's partnership with Northwestern Mutual will happen in phases, with money being invested as the",
        "bbox": [
          0.5047801147227533,
          0.32625129306914935,
          0.6583811344805609,
          0.36444656640407413
        ],
        "order": 29
      },
      {
        "id": "mineru_newspaper_The Wall Street Journal - 2025-01-08@magazinesclubnew_page_021_17",
        "observed_type": "text",
        "canon_role": "support_paragraph",
        "text": "Wall Street's big push into insurance got under way after Apollo Global Management began managing the assets of Athene, an insurance com-",
        "bbox": [
          0.33906947100063733,
          0.3329354659027612,
          0.4945825366475462,
          0.36444656640407413
        ],
        "order": 30
      },
      {
        "id": "mineru_newspaper_The Wall Street Journal - 2025-01-08@magazinesclubnew_page_021_6",
        "observed_type": "text",
        "canon_role": "support_paragraph",
        "text": "Citrin Cooperman has grown significantly in the roughly four years since the sale. The firm reported $351.8 million in revenue in 2021. Its 2024 revenue totaled about $900 million, in part due to acquisitions of smaller firms, people familiar said.",
        "bbox": [
          0.012746972594008922,
          0.34566722368106945,
          0.16443594646271512,
          0.3647648603485319
        ],
        "order": 31
      },
      {
        "id": "mineru_newspaper_The Wall Street Journal - 2025-01-08@magazinesclubnew_page_021_10",
        "observed_type": "text",
        "canon_role": "support_paragraph",
        "text": "ness of accounting firms. The Financial Times first reported on the deal.",
        "bbox": [
          0.17590822179732313,
          0.3469403994589003,
          0.32887189292543023,
          0.36444656640407413
        ],
        "order": 32
      },
      {
        "id": "mineru_newspaper_The Wall Street Journal - 2025-01-08@magazinesclubnew_page_021_43",
        "observed_type": "text",
        "canon_role": "support_paragraph",
        "text": "",
        "bbox": [
          0.8330146590184832,
          0.37781491207129786,
          0.9923518164435946,
          0.48412508952017186
        ],
        "order": 34
      },
      {
        "id": "mineru_newspaper_The Wall Street Journal - 2025-01-08@magazinesclubnew_page_021_36",
        "observed_type": "text",
        "canon_role": "support_paragraph",
        "text": "",
        "bbox": [
          0.17654557042702357,
          0.402641839738999,
          0.32950924155513067,
          0.43478952812922733
        ],
        "order": 36
      },
      {
        "id": "mineru_newspaper_The Wall Street Journal - 2025-01-08@magazinesclubnew_page_021_40",
        "observed_type": "text",
        "canon_role": "support_paragraph",
        "text": "",
        "bbox": [
          0.5041427660930529,
          0.402641839738999,
          0.65710643722116,
          0.49208243813161456
        ],
        "order": 37
      },
      {
        "id": "mineru_newspaper_The Wall Street Journal - 2025-01-08@magazinesclubnew_page_021_41",
        "observed_type": "text",
        "canon_role": "support_paragraph",
        "text": "",
        "bbox": [
          0.668578712555768,
          0.402641839738999,
          0.8215423836838751,
          0.4532505769077743
        ],
        "order": 38
      },
      {
        "id": "mineru_newspaper_The Wall Street Journal - 2025-01-08@magazinesclubnew_page_021_38",
        "observed_type": "text",
        "canon_role": "support_paragraph",
        "text": "Behnam has sought a lead- ing role for the CFTC in regu- lating the cryptocurrency market, which has defied easy categorization within the fi- nancial regulatory system. That has put the derivatives regulator in a potential con- flict with the Securities and Exchange Commission around jurisdictional power over the nascent industry.",
        "bbox": [
          0.3397068196303378,
          0.4086894246836954,
          0.49394518801784576,
          0.48635314713137584
        ],
        "order": 39
      },
      {
        "id": "mineru_newspaper_The Wall Street Journal - 2025-01-08@magazinesclubnew_page_021_34",
        "observed_type": "text",
        "canon_role": "support_paragraph",
        "text": "Commodity Futures Trad- ing Commission Chairman Rostin Behnam said he would step down from his position on Jan. 20, as the country's top derivatives markets regu- lator prepares for a second Trump term.",
        "bbox": [
          0.012109623964308477,
          0.41505530357284953,
          0.16379859783301465,
          0.4663006286305403
        ],
        "order": 40
      },
      {
        "id": "mineru_newspaper_The Wall Street Journal - 2025-01-08@magazinesclubnew_page_021_37",
        "observed_type": "text",
        "canon_role": "support_paragraph",
        "text": "Behnam said that under his leadership, the CFTC shifted its focus from implementing the 2010 Dodd-Frank Act to adapting its oversight respon- sibilities to address the new issues brought on by evolving technology in the derivatives markets and to tackle regula-",
        "bbox": [
          0.17654557042702357,
          0.4341529402403119,
          0.32887189292543023,
          0.49144585024269916
        ],
        "order": 41
      },
      {
        "id": "mineru_newspaper_The Wall Street Journal - 2025-01-08@magazinesclubnew_page_021_42",
        "observed_type": "text",
        "canon_role": "support_paragraph",
        "text": "Behnam said his last day at the agency will be Feb. 7, add- ing that he would work closely with President-elect Donald Trump's team to ensure a smooth transition.",
        "bbox": [
          0.6692160611854685,
          0.453568870852232,
          0.8215423836838751,
          0.49176414418715686
        ],
        "order": 42
      },
      {
        "id": "mineru_newspaper_The Wall Street Journal - 2025-01-08@magazinesclubnew_page_021_35",
        "observed_type": "text",
        "canon_role": "support_paragraph",
        "text": "Behnam, a Democrat, has served as the CFTC's chairman since 2022. He previously served as a commissioner be- tween 2017 and 2021 and was named acting chairman in 2021 after his predecessor, Heath Tarbert, resigned when President Biden took office.",
        "bbox": [
          0.012746972594008922,
          0.466618922574998,
          0.16379859783301465,
          0.49176414418715686
        ],
        "order": 43
      },
      {
        "id": "mineru_newspaper_The Wall Street Journal - 2025-01-08@magazinesclubnew_page_021_45",
        "observed_type": "image_caption",
        "canon_role": "support_paragraph",
        "text": "The CFTC's Rostin Behnam.",
        "bbox": [
          0.8330146590184832,
          0.48539826529800273,
